WEBVTT

00:09.994 --> 00:12.249
‐ [speaks Arabic]

00:14.211 --> 00:17.008
Mohamed? Mohamed?

00:17.008 --> 00:19.973
‐ This is Ayman al‐Zawahiri.

00:19.973 --> 00:24.398
Tell the Americans we can take
on the United States.

00:24.398 --> 00:27.822
The war has only just begun.

00:27.822 --> 00:30.285
‐ Anybody else handle
this device besides you?

00:30.285 --> 00:32.372
‐ I said I locked it up, man.
‐ Okay.

00:32.372 --> 00:34.126
‐ What exactly do you want
from me?

00:34.126 --> 00:37.550
‐ I definitely want us
to be more than buddies.

00:37.550 --> 00:40.513
‐ You've been flagged
for recent expense patterns.

00:40.513 --> 00:42.560
‐ I'm having dinner and drinks
with important people.

00:42.560 --> 00:44.647
‐ You need to start living
within your means.

00:44.647 --> 00:46.568
‐ Sir, your card
has been declined.

00:46.568 --> 00:48.739
‐ Really?
‐ There is a chain of command

00:48.739 --> 00:50.576
by which decisions are made.

00:50.576 --> 00:53.039
Your boss has yet to learn
this lesson.

00:53.039 --> 00:56.420
‐ Use the chain of command.
It exists for a reason.

00:56.420 --> 00:59.176
In other words, get the hell
out of my office.

00:59.176 --> 01:01.973
‐ Sanchez, you and Louie
can go fuck yourselves.

01:01.973 --> 01:05.396
‐ By the way, that open slot
heading up the New York office?

01:05.396 --> 01:08.987
I just found out Louis Freeh's
D. C. guy got the job.

01:08.987 --> 01:12.369
Sanchez. One of the best.

01:12.369 --> 01:14.414
DIANE: Martin,
you started this.

01:14.414 --> 01:16.210
Nobody else
at the Agency foresaw

01:16.210 --> 01:17.672
what's happening with al‐Qaeda.

01:17.672 --> 01:19.717
You are the prophet.

01:19.717 --> 01:23.140
You have my undivided devotion,
Martin.

01:23.140 --> 01:25.186
‐ They sent a fucking cable

01:25.186 --> 01:27.983
saying that this guy is
coming into our country,

01:27.983 --> 01:30.739
that he has a Saudi passport
and a U. S. Visa.

01:30.739 --> 01:32.200
‐ Welcome to America, sir.

01:32.200 --> 01:34.121
‐ 53 people
from the CIA have read it,

01:34.121 --> 01:35.582
and we're not sharing this yet?

01:35.582 --> 01:37.502
‐ Diane will tell us
when we can share.

01:37.502 --> 01:39.381
‐ I'm calling O'Neill.
‐ Wait.

01:39.381 --> 01:41.673
There's a reason for the wall.
There is a reason.

01:41.673 --> 01:42.708
[both speaking Arabic]

01:50.571 --> 01:52.449
‐ They're here.

01:52.449 --> 01:54.494
They're here in America.

01:54.494 --> 01:57.125
We have no idea
what we're up against.

02:14.149 --> 02:15.157
‐ [speaking Arabic]

02:52.517 --> 02:55.241
[automatic gunfire]

02:55.241 --> 02:57.538
[crowd commotion]

02:57.538 --> 03:00.293
<i>[dark music]</i>

03:04.802 --> 03:06.931
‐ We are Muslims.

03:06.931 --> 03:10.522
We are Muslims who believe
in their religion,

03:10.522 --> 03:13.068
both in ideology and practice,

03:13.068 --> 03:15.616
and hence,
we tried our best

03:15.616 --> 03:19.540
to establish this Islamic
state and Islamic society.

03:19.540 --> 03:21.126
We have sacrificed,

03:21.126 --> 03:23.250
and we are still ready
for more sacrifices.

03:23.250 --> 03:24.285
ZAWAHIRI: [speaking Arabic]

03:33.400 --> 03:37.367
<i>[solemn Middle‐Eastern music]</i>

03:37.367 --> 03:38.703
<i>♪ ♪</i>

03:38.703 --> 03:39.891
[gunfire]

05:09.217 --> 05:13.517
Your English is perfect.

05:15.062 --> 05:16.566
‐ No one is perfect.

05:18.026 --> 05:21.617
‐ I want to rely on you

05:21.617 --> 05:24.999
to fix things for us
in America.

05:26.836 --> 05:31.052
‐ Dr. Zawahiri,
I'm at your service.

05:31.052 --> 05:33.725
I will do all that I can.

05:33.725 --> 05:37.481
[video game sounds]

05:37.481 --> 05:40.655
<i>[ambient music]</i>

05:40.655 --> 05:44.997
<i>♪ ♪</i>

05:44.997 --> 05:47.168
‐ [speaking Arabic]

05:51.802 --> 05:54.767
[both speaking Arabic]

05:54.767 --> 05:57.271
[laughter]

06:05.496 --> 06:08.502
[birds chirping]

06:19.274 --> 06:21.069
[keyboard clacking]

06:34.680 --> 06:37.476
[computer chimes]

06:56.724 --> 06:59.563
[computer chimes]

07:22.233 --> 07:23.736
‐ This is the world
you're dealing with.

07:23.736 --> 07:27.953
This potentially explosive,
dangerous world.

07:27.953 --> 07:31.167
Your situation needs to be
handled with discretion.

07:31.167 --> 07:32.671
So long as you're here,

07:32.671 --> 07:36.511
Alec Station's been left
in good hands.

07:36.511 --> 07:39.308
I believe that.

07:39.308 --> 07:42.314
‐ I was taught well.

07:42.314 --> 07:44.443
‐ Let's examine...

07:44.443 --> 07:47.032
You've built an operation
based outside this country.

07:47.032 --> 07:49.370
‐ That's where all roads lead.
‐ Away from here.

07:49.370 --> 07:50.790
‐ Southeast Asia.

07:50.790 --> 07:52.586
‐ So, take a step back

07:52.586 --> 07:54.255
and look
at the intelligence structure

07:54.255 --> 07:56.552
that you've put together
painstakingly.

07:56.552 --> 07:58.305
Should you hand
over the keys to this house

07:58.305 --> 08:00.810
so soon after its construction?

08:00.810 --> 08:02.939
Do you allow others
to unlock doors,

08:02.939 --> 08:07.072
to poke around,
remove posts and beams?

08:07.072 --> 08:11.456
Collapse the intricate
structure that you've erected?

08:11.456 --> 08:13.836
This is the decision
you need to make.

08:13.836 --> 08:16.382
You have the clarity of mind
and sense of purpose

08:16.382 --> 08:18.386
to arrive at the right choice.

08:18.386 --> 08:21.392
<i>[reflective music]</i>

08:21.392 --> 08:28.365
<i>♪ ♪</i>

08:45.900 --> 08:47.737
‐ Are you writing a book?

08:49.908 --> 08:52.747
‐ I'm not sure yet what it is.
Maybe. It may be a book.

08:54.793 --> 08:56.462
‐ Can I ask what it's about?

08:59.302 --> 09:01.306
‐ I try to follow
Samuel Clemens' dictum

09:01.306 --> 09:04.270
of write what you know.

09:04.270 --> 09:06.441
I don't know much,
but what I do know I know well.

09:06.441 --> 09:09.656
‐ You know me better
than anyone ever has.

09:18.298 --> 09:20.887
‐ Can I be...I need
to be perfectly honest.

09:20.887 --> 09:22.306
‐ It's okay, I shouldn't‐‐
‐ No.

09:22.306 --> 09:24.561
‐ I'm sorry, I‐‐
‐ No, will you please‐‐

09:33.453 --> 09:35.792
[footsteps]

09:35.792 --> 09:38.798
[water running]

09:40.677 --> 09:42.764
[door opens]

09:42.764 --> 09:45.728
[footsteps recede]

09:49.443 --> 09:51.949
‐ Nothing.

09:51.949 --> 09:53.703
Still nothing.

09:53.703 --> 09:56.165
‐ She's probably trying
to get some answers for you.

09:56.165 --> 09:59.213
‐ Really. You think?
‐ Could be.

09:59.213 --> 10:02.469
I don't know why you keep
assuming the worst in people.

10:02.469 --> 10:06.060
‐ I think we saw something
we weren't supposed to see.

10:15.203 --> 10:16.209
‐ [speaking Arabic]

10:26.367 --> 10:27.377
[both speaking Arabic]

10:33.616 --> 10:36.287
‐ How do you say cunt
in Arabic?

10:40.462 --> 10:43.051
‐ She wants you in her office
in three minutes.

10:43.051 --> 10:45.681
‐ Oh, three minutes?

10:45.681 --> 10:48.269
Not two? Not four?

10:48.269 --> 10:51.275
‐ She said three.

10:51.275 --> 10:53.488
[knocking at door]
‐ Come.

10:56.662 --> 10:58.498
‐ You wanted to see‐‐
‐ Close the door.

11:06.807 --> 11:08.811
You are, at times,
on the receiving end

11:08.811 --> 11:10.606
of classified intelligence.

11:10.606 --> 11:12.986
‐ More than 50 people inside
Langley know about Mihdhar.

11:12.986 --> 11:14.906
‐ You need to understand
something,

11:14.906 --> 11:18.496
and I want you to understand it
deeply and clearly.

11:18.496 --> 11:19.958
You are never the decider

11:19.958 --> 11:22.087
of what to do
with that intelligence.

11:22.087 --> 11:24.049
[compact snaps shut]
You may recall a night

11:24.049 --> 11:26.387
when you endeavored to remove
classified materials

11:26.387 --> 11:27.932
from this office.

11:27.932 --> 11:30.145
The Professor
was forgiving enough

11:30.145 --> 11:32.316
not to prosecute you.

11:32.316 --> 11:36.240
I am not so forgiving.

11:36.240 --> 11:38.704
When you receive
classified intelligence,

11:38.704 --> 11:41.292
either by happenstance
or by design,

11:41.292 --> 11:44.591
if you reveal that intelligence
to anyone outside this Station,

11:44.591 --> 11:48.431
intelligence that I have not
personally cleared,

11:48.431 --> 11:51.103
I will see to it
that you are handcuffed,

11:51.103 --> 11:53.441
that you are escorted
from this building,

11:53.441 --> 11:56.907
that you are imprisoned and
tried for theft and treason.

11:56.907 --> 11:58.368
[lipstick snaps shut]

11:59.955 --> 12:01.374
Now get the fuck
out of my office

12:01.374 --> 12:03.169
and close the door
behind you.

12:21.080 --> 12:24.086
[indistinct conversation]

12:45.170 --> 12:47.717
‐ Vince. Thanks for coming by.

12:47.717 --> 12:49.971
Good to see you.
‐ Found it, finally.

12:49.971 --> 12:53.394
‐ You've been up here before.
‐ Ah, I've never been upstairs.

12:53.394 --> 12:55.440
They keep us squirreled
away in the basement.

12:55.440 --> 12:57.528
This whole visitor deal

12:57.528 --> 12:59.406
between the Agency and
the Bureau, there's a reason

12:59.406 --> 13:01.452
we call it the
hostage‐exchange program.

13:01.452 --> 13:03.498
‐ [chuckles softly]

13:03.498 --> 13:05.586
Can I get you a drink?

13:05.586 --> 13:08.216
‐ Oh, uh‐‐
‐ We just put in a long day

13:08.216 --> 13:11.640
keeping America safe.
I think we deserve a scotch.

13:11.640 --> 13:14.771
Yes?
‐ Uh, sure.

13:14.771 --> 13:17.777
Has been a long day.
Okay.

13:17.777 --> 13:20.574
‐ Are you married, Vince?

13:20.574 --> 13:22.035
In a relationship?

13:22.035 --> 13:23.872
‐ Uh, not married.

13:23.872 --> 13:26.377
In a, you know,

13:26.377 --> 13:28.799
relationship or two.

13:28.799 --> 13:31.847
‐ I remember those days.

13:31.847 --> 13:35.646
Makes it easier.

13:35.646 --> 13:39.236
‐ I'm not following.
‐ Oh, right. [laughs]

13:39.236 --> 13:41.240
Let me back up.

13:41.240 --> 13:44.288
I'm trying to make some changes
at Alec Station,

13:44.288 --> 13:46.041
and one of them is making sure

13:46.041 --> 13:47.837
that as many operations
as possible are done

13:47.837 --> 13:49.799
hand‐in‐hand with the Bureau.

13:49.799 --> 13:52.053
The best work between
the Agency and the FBI

13:52.053 --> 13:54.391
is done on the ground,
out in the field.

13:54.391 --> 13:57.480
And I hate to see
an experienced agent like you

13:57.480 --> 14:00.361
stuck in a windowless cubicle
day after day.

14:00.361 --> 14:03.827
Especially one who speaks,
how many languages? Three?

14:03.827 --> 14:05.413
‐ Four, actually.

14:05.413 --> 14:08.377
Well, including English.

14:08.377 --> 14:11.300
‐ Well, French, Spanish‐‐
‐ And Italian.

14:11.300 --> 14:13.429
‐ Impressive.

14:16.268 --> 14:19.817
We have an operation
in Morocco next week.

14:19.817 --> 14:22.322
Now, I would be happy
to reach out to your boss,

14:22.322 --> 14:25.788
but maybe you should talk
to him yourself.

14:25.788 --> 14:29.712
What do you think?

14:29.712 --> 14:33.260
‐ So...

14:33.260 --> 14:35.808
so I wouldn't be
the responsible liaison anymore

14:35.808 --> 14:37.603
between Alec and I‐49?

14:37.603 --> 14:39.481
‐ You would gather intel
firsthand,

14:39.481 --> 14:43.030
in the field, and pass it
directly to the Bureau.

14:45.869 --> 14:49.251
‐ Well, uh,

14:49.251 --> 14:51.548
I'll tell you
the honest to God truth‐‐

14:51.548 --> 14:54.386
I'd love to get the hell
out of this office.

14:54.386 --> 14:57.392
Travel a bit, get back
to what I used to do.

14:57.392 --> 14:59.689
‐ [chuckles] I'd like
that for you too.

15:01.985 --> 15:05.199
We've reached an understanding?

15:20.021 --> 15:23.027
<i>[pensive music]</i>

15:23.027 --> 15:30.041
<i>♪ ♪</i>

15:58.807 --> 16:01.813
<i>[hip‐hop music]</i>

16:01.813 --> 16:08.785
<i>♪ ♪</i>

16:10.831 --> 16:13.837
<i>[hip‐hop music fades]</i>

16:17.302 --> 16:19.139
‐ How you settling in, boss?

16:19.139 --> 16:21.018
Much better view
than you had in D. C.

16:21.018 --> 16:23.147
‐ Hello, John. Good to see you.
‐ You all set up?

16:23.147 --> 16:25.067
I can help find you
an apartment if you need one.

16:25.067 --> 16:26.571
I‐‐I got people
all over the city.

16:26.571 --> 16:28.240
‐ I have a realtor looking.

16:28.240 --> 16:30.119
I prefer not to be beholden
to anybody out there

16:30.119 --> 16:32.708
doing me a special favor.
You understand.

16:32.708 --> 16:36.966
‐ Sure. Sure, of course.
Uh, listen, these are for you.

16:36.966 --> 16:38.803
Welcome to Gotham.

16:38.803 --> 16:40.641
I want to say, um,
you know I've had

16:40.641 --> 16:43.103
had my differences
with Director Freeh.

16:43.103 --> 16:45.191
On occasion with you too.

16:45.191 --> 16:46.736
But I hope we can
make a fresh start,

16:46.736 --> 16:48.405
bury the hatchet.

16:48.405 --> 16:50.284
I want you to know
that I'm here to support you.

16:50.284 --> 16:53.708
I'm on your team.
You tell me what you need.

16:53.708 --> 16:56.756
‐ I appreciate that, John.
I really do.

16:56.756 --> 16:58.969
And I'm glad you stopped by.

16:58.969 --> 17:00.889
Would you sit for a sec?

17:00.889 --> 17:04.563
‐ Yep. Yeah.
[both sigh]

17:04.563 --> 17:07.068
‐ A couple of things.

17:07.068 --> 17:09.364
As you can imagine,
I've been briefed

17:09.364 --> 17:12.412
on the ongoing investigation
into your finances.

17:12.412 --> 17:15.167
I hope you will continue
to cooperate.

17:15.167 --> 17:17.380
‐ Yes. Of course.

17:17.380 --> 17:19.092
‐ On an unrelated note,

17:19.092 --> 17:21.221
it's come to my attention
that you're nearing

17:21.221 --> 17:23.810
your 25th year at the Bureau.

17:28.402 --> 17:31.784
‐ This is an unrelated note?
‐ It's standard procedure.

17:31.784 --> 17:35.499
Mandatory for anybody coming up
on their 25th year.

17:35.499 --> 17:38.005
You learn the pension benefits,
health care,

17:38.005 --> 17:39.634
a little financial
planning advice,

17:39.634 --> 17:42.472
and you get
a free trip to Florida.

17:42.472 --> 17:44.977
‐ You know, there's several
guys who are a lot older

17:44.977 --> 17:46.564
than me
floating around the office.

17:46.564 --> 17:48.192
‐ And they're gonna get
their dates as well.

17:48.192 --> 17:49.737
But this week is for you.

17:49.737 --> 17:51.574
‐ Things are pretty busy
this week.

17:51.574 --> 17:54.245
‐ It's mandatory.

17:57.251 --> 18:00.257
‐ All right.
I can visit Space Mountain.

18:00.257 --> 18:02.220
‐ Whatever works for you.

18:06.896 --> 18:08.525
‐ It's good talking to you.

18:08.525 --> 18:10.779
Welcome to New York.
Congrats on the promotion.

18:10.779 --> 18:12.407
See you at the end of the week.

18:12.407 --> 18:14.704
‐ John.

18:14.704 --> 18:17.710
I appreciate the gift.
I really do, but I don't smoke.

18:17.710 --> 18:19.714
You'll get more use
out of these than I will.

18:25.642 --> 18:28.021
‐ I'm not replacing these
with a heart‐shaped box

18:28.021 --> 18:30.067
of chocolates, if that's
what you're looking for.

18:30.067 --> 18:34.451
‐ Understood. I don't eat
much chocolate anyway.

18:34.451 --> 18:36.037
‐ [under breath]
I bet you don't.

18:36.037 --> 18:38.668
‐ And John.
Those aren't Cubans are they?

18:38.668 --> 18:42.300
'Cause last I checked, we still
have an embargo with Castro.

18:42.300 --> 18:45.222
‐ No clue.
I was re‐gifting.

18:47.770 --> 18:50.734
<i>[Latin rhythm music]</i>

18:50.734 --> 18:52.403
<i>♪ ♪</i>

18:52.403 --> 18:54.950
[cheers and applause]

18:58.958 --> 19:00.503
‐ So, the good news for y'all,

19:00.503 --> 19:02.841
given that you've passed
that 20‐year mark,

19:02.841 --> 19:06.306
given that you're coming up
on year 25‐‐yay‐‐

19:06.306 --> 19:08.268
is that you're moving
from the possibility

19:08.268 --> 19:11.734
of half‐pay retirement
into three‐quarters pay,

19:11.734 --> 19:13.947
which is as high
as you're gonna get.

19:13.947 --> 19:15.366
[cell phone buzzing]
Y'all have reached

19:15.366 --> 19:18.247
the mountaintop, people.
Enjoy the view.

19:18.247 --> 19:19.834
Also, completely separate...
‐ Yeah.

19:19.834 --> 19:22.296
SHERI: Hey, guess
who's almost done packing?

19:22.296 --> 19:24.133
‐ Packing? Packing for what?

19:24.133 --> 19:26.639
‐ Oh, you shut up.
You know for what.

19:26.639 --> 19:28.475
And I'm gonna get there
in New York City

19:28.475 --> 19:30.856
and I'm gonna break out my
stash of Victoria's Secret,

19:30.856 --> 19:34.237
and I'm gonna blow
your freakin' mind.

19:34.237 --> 19:36.366
‐ Wait. Is it Mom?

19:36.366 --> 19:38.161
‐ [chuckles] Johnny.

19:38.161 --> 19:40.040
You're disgusting.

19:40.040 --> 19:42.336
Don't you pretend
you don't know who this is.

19:42.336 --> 19:44.507
Don't you pretend you
haven't been crying yourself

19:44.507 --> 19:48.140
to sleep every night just
waiting for me to get there.

19:48.140 --> 19:49.935
I hope you're clearing
space in your dresser

19:49.935 --> 19:51.647
for my new panties.

19:51.647 --> 19:53.442
‐ Oh. Uh...

19:53.442 --> 19:56.908
‐ Don't worry. They're
teeny, teeny tiny, Johnny.

19:56.908 --> 19:58.536
‐ Darling, listen,
I got you a sweet apartment

19:58.536 --> 19:59.830
for the time being.

19:59.830 --> 20:01.876
‐ You what?

20:01.876 --> 20:03.503
I thought I was
moving in with you.

20:03.503 --> 20:04.924
‐ No, no. Not just yet.
Not right now.

20:04.924 --> 20:06.677
I've got some linguists
staying with me.

20:06.677 --> 20:09.140
‐ You what?
‐ Some linguists.

20:09.140 --> 20:11.061
Doing some translating.

20:23.126 --> 20:24.922
[clears throat]

20:34.440 --> 20:36.319
[breathing heavily]

20:50.514 --> 20:52.393
Security.
I need to talk to security.

20:52.393 --> 20:53.855
‐ Yes, sir.
Can I ask your room?

20:53.855 --> 20:55.817
‐ Now.
‐ Yes, sir.

20:55.817 --> 20:58.321
Um, yes, we need someone
at the front desk right away.

20:58.321 --> 21:00.492
Okay, thank you.

21:04.459 --> 21:07.758
‐ Three hours. It's out
of my hands for three hours.

21:07.758 --> 21:09.970
‐ Okay.

21:09.970 --> 21:12.058
‐ Found it in a dumpster
around back.

21:12.058 --> 21:14.897
‐ So what's missing?

21:14.897 --> 21:17.986
‐ Uh, cash. 500 bucks.
Cigar cutter.

21:17.986 --> 21:19.823
‐ The gold one?
‐ Yeah.

21:19.823 --> 21:22.495
‐ And what about
the classified papers?

21:22.495 --> 21:25.794
‐ Uh, all there.
There‐‐

21:25.794 --> 21:28.549
But...
‐ What?

21:30.385 --> 21:33.851
‐ Nothing. It...It‐‐it seems
like they weren't messed with.

21:33.851 --> 21:36.272
It seems like...

21:36.272 --> 21:37.859
simple robbery.

21:37.859 --> 21:39.696
‐ But there's no way
to tell for sure.

21:39.696 --> 21:41.282
‐ No.

21:45.332 --> 21:47.461
So...

21:53.390 --> 21:55.394
Do I tell him?

21:55.394 --> 21:57.816
‐ Um, John. I...

21:57.816 --> 21:59.736
I'm an English Professor.
I'm not‐‐

21:59.736 --> 22:01.657
‐ You're an ethical person.
You're a logical thinker.

22:01.657 --> 22:03.786
Help me out.

22:06.876 --> 22:08.754
‐ Okay.

22:10.842 --> 22:13.180
[exhales slowly]

22:13.180 --> 22:15.810
I think there are two issues.

22:15.810 --> 22:19.568
The first is the moral one.
You broke the rules.

22:19.568 --> 22:24.118
So you decide whether it's
important to turn yourself in.

22:24.118 --> 22:27.041
The second issue‐‐
what if something happens

22:27.041 --> 22:30.172
as a result of the documents
being read?

22:30.172 --> 22:34.932
They weren't taken,
but they might have been read.

22:34.932 --> 22:36.977
I don't know what's in them,

22:36.977 --> 22:40.652
but I assume they're classified
for a reason.

22:44.242 --> 22:45.787
Am I right?

22:48.375 --> 22:50.797
John?

22:50.797 --> 22:53.803
‐ [distressed breathing]

23:06.578 --> 23:10.502
‐ John. Thanks for coming in.

23:10.502 --> 23:12.339
Go ahead, Mike.

23:16.389 --> 23:19.646
‐ We dusted the entire case,
inside and out.

23:19.646 --> 23:23.320
Several distinct, identifiable
fingerprints on the exterior,

23:23.320 --> 23:26.200
including yours, Mr. O'Neill,
your secretary's,

23:26.200 --> 23:28.789
two members
of the hotel security staff,

23:28.789 --> 23:31.587
and one other we didn't have
in the database.

23:31.587 --> 23:33.089
As for
the classified documents,

23:33.089 --> 23:34.885
we found two sets of prints‐‐

23:34.885 --> 23:38.809
yours and your secretary's.

23:38.809 --> 23:41.565
‐ I looked at the forensics
and the criminal report,

23:41.565 --> 23:43.485
and we feel it's safe to assume

23:43.485 --> 23:45.447
that this is a simple case
of robbery.

23:45.447 --> 23:49.623
‐ Oh. Oh...
[chuckles]

23:49.623 --> 23:52.378
Oh, thank you.
Oh...[sniffs]

23:52.378 --> 23:54.256
[exhales]
All right, all right.

23:54.256 --> 23:55.802
Well, I hope we can...

23:55.802 --> 23:58.390
hope we can put this to bed
now and move on.

23:58.390 --> 24:01.270
Keep it internal,
within the New York Office.

24:08.368 --> 24:10.038
‐ John...

24:10.038 --> 24:12.669
can you tell us what happened
a few months ago

24:12.669 --> 24:15.298
with your Palm Pilot?

24:15.298 --> 24:16.718
‐ Excuse me?

24:16.718 --> 24:18.221
‐ It's come to our attention

24:18.221 --> 24:19.975
that it was out
of your possession

24:19.975 --> 24:21.937
for a period of time
and that it was returned to you

24:21.937 --> 24:23.566
by a D. C. transit cop.

24:23.566 --> 24:25.360
‐ Who brought it
to your attention?

24:25.360 --> 24:27.197
‐ That's not important.

24:27.197 --> 24:29.368
‐ It's important to me.
It's my personal device.

24:29.368 --> 24:30.705
It's none of your business

24:30.705 --> 24:32.374
whether it was out
of my possession.

24:32.374 --> 24:34.295
‐ I think it's fairly clear,
that given what was

24:34.295 --> 24:36.550
in your briefcase, you're
not terrific at separating

24:36.550 --> 24:39.890
the professional
from the personal.

24:39.890 --> 24:42.311
Mike's gonna have
to inspect it,

24:42.311 --> 24:44.900
make sure there's
no classified contacts,

24:44.900 --> 24:48.239
determine whether anything
was electronically copied.

24:55.462 --> 24:57.216
‐ Have fun.

25:01.516 --> 25:04.313
You done with this?

25:04.313 --> 25:06.652
‐ Yes, sir. I am.
‐ You sure‐‐you sure?

25:06.652 --> 25:08.071
‐ Yes, sir.

25:19.719 --> 25:21.557
‐ Nice shoes, man.
What the fuck?

25:21.557 --> 25:24.061
‐ Boss wasn't crazy about
what I was wearing before.

25:24.061 --> 25:27.150
‐ Ferragamos, dude?
For moving furniture?

25:27.150 --> 25:29.029
‐ They're weirdly comfortable.

25:29.029 --> 25:31.535
‐ Tell me about it,
I got six pair.

25:33.539 --> 25:35.375
‐ And I was working today.

25:35.375 --> 25:37.379
I didn't have time to change

25:37.379 --> 25:39.843
into my designer track suit
and Air Pippens.

25:39.843 --> 25:42.557
‐ Oh, shit. You bustin' on me,
you little bitch?

25:42.557 --> 25:44.101
Finally get a day off Langley,

25:44.101 --> 25:46.523
you bustin' my chops
about my clothes?

25:46.523 --> 25:48.527
‐ No, it's a good look.
Works for you.

25:48.527 --> 25:50.280
‐ You're fucking right it does.

25:50.280 --> 25:51.825
And they're Pippen 2s,
you cocksucker.

25:51.825 --> 25:53.829
‐ Oh, my God, you guys,
thank you so much.

25:53.829 --> 25:55.541
You're the greatest.
It's one flight up.

25:55.541 --> 25:57.294
On the right hand side.

25:57.294 --> 25:58.797
Johnny was supposed to be here.
‐ We got it, Sheri.

25:58.797 --> 26:00.216
‐ I don't know where he is.
‐ It's all good.

26:00.216 --> 26:02.597
‐ [softly] He's here?
‐ [softly] Yeah.

26:07.690 --> 26:09.401
‐ [high pitched squeal]
John!

26:09.401 --> 26:11.865
[laughing] Oh, you're here.

26:11.865 --> 26:14.370
You're here. [squeals]
‐ Yeah, baby.

26:14.370 --> 26:15.956
[both laughing]
Oh, I missed you.

26:15.956 --> 26:18.837
I missed you, I missed you.
Oh, I miss‐‐

26:18.837 --> 26:20.758
I missed you so much.

26:20.758 --> 26:22.720
You're not even tan,
weren't you in Florida?

26:22.720 --> 26:24.683
‐ Uh, yeah, yeah.
‐ God, I missed you.

26:24.683 --> 26:26.728
How are you?
‐ I'm perfect.

26:26.728 --> 26:30.569
Everything's perfect.
Especially now.

26:30.569 --> 26:32.699
SPORTSCASTER:..have become
the second catcher

26:32.699 --> 26:34.034
